## Potions
#### Antimagic Potion
*Potion, legendary*

When you drink this potion, you become the focus of the *antimagic field* spell for 10 minutes (no concentration required). Upon close inspection, small flecks of gold can be seen swirling in the clear liquid of this potion. When unstopped, it begins to bubble and seethe like a cauldron set to boiling.

#### Bottle of Plague
(Potion of poison, but for diseases.)

#### Gift of Arthas
This bright blue potion shimmers, gleaming and glittering in sunlight. Anyone tasting it has his spirits briefly lifted, as if a wave of happiness flowed through them.

The gift of Arthas provides resistance 10 against any damage caused by a spell or effect from the necromancy school, such as a death coil. Furthermore, anyone striking the user in melee combat must make a DC 14 Will save or take a –4 penalty to Strength (to a minimum of 1) for 1d6+1 rounds. The effects of this elixir last for 10 minutes.

#### Kuzko's Poison
Turns you into a llama, permanently.
Or a potion of polymorph.

#### Noth's Special Brew

#### Potion of Climbing
*Potion, common*

When you drink this potion, you gain a climbing speed equal to your walking speed for 1 hour. During this time, you have advantage on Strength (Athletics) checks you make to climb. The potion is separated into brown, silver, and gray layers resembling bands of stone. Shaking the bottle fails to mix the colors.

#### Potion of Dreamless Sleep
This substance appears much like a gas while held within its vial. The swirling blue vapor flows like a liquid when poured, however, allowing it to be easily contained. If sniffed or tasted, the subject becomes mildly drowsy for a few moments, but suffers no other ill effects.

When consumed, the imbiber falls into a deep, dreamless sleep for 10 minutes. During this time he cannot be revived by any means. At the conclusion of the effect’s duration, he arises, feeling refreshed. The sleep heals him of 3d8+5 points of damage, cures 1d4 points of ability score damage (if any), and allows him to recover up to 5 levels of spell slots.

#### Potion of Energy
(Gives energy points. Unknown effect if used by non-energy user.)

#### Potion of Focus
(Gives focus points. Unknown effect if used by non-focus user.)

#### Potion of Healing
*Potion, rarity varies*

You regain a number of hit points when you drink this potion. The number of hit points depends on the potion's rarity, as shown in the Potions of Healing table. Whatever its potency, the potion's red liquid glimmers when agitated.

##### Potions of Healing
Potion of...    | Rarity    | HP Regained
----------------|-----------|----------
Healing         | Common    | 2d4 + 2
Greater Healing | Uncommon  | 4d4 + 4
Superior Healing| Rare      | 8d4 + 8
Supreme Healing | Very Rare | 10d4 + 20

#### Potion of Invisibility
*Potion, very rare*

This potion's container looks empty but feels as though it holds liquid. When you drink it, you become invisible for 1 hour. Anything you wear or carry is invisible with you. The effect ends early if you attack or cast a spell.

#### Potion of Invulnerability
*Potion, legendary*

For 1 minute after you drink this potion, you have immunity to all damage. The potion's syrupy liquid looks like liquefied iron.

#### Potion of Limited Invulnerability
*Potion, rare*

For 1 minute after you drink this potion, you have resistance to all damage. The potion's syrupy liquid looks like liquefied bronze.

#### Potion of Lion's Strength
(Single person bless effect. Name comes from the usage by a Stormwind infantry unit to turn the tide of a battle.)

#### Potion of Mana
*Potion, rarity varies*

You regain a number of expended spell slots when you drink this potion. The number of spell slots can have a combined level that is equal to or lesser than a number determined by the potion's rarity, as shown in the Potions of Mana table, and none of the slots can be 6th level or higher.

You have learned to regain some of your magical energy by studying your spellbook. Once per day when you finish a short rest, you can choose expended spell slots to recover. The spell slots can have a combined level that is equal to or less than half your wizard level (rounded up), and none of the slots can be 6th level or higher.

Drinking a potion of mana puts strain on your soul. If you drink a second such potion before you finish a short or long rest, you must make a Constitution saving throw or take damage as shown on the Potions of Mana table. Whatever its potency, the potion's blue liquid sheds soft light.

[Source](https://www.reddit.com/r/UnearthedArcana/comments/5wm4t1/mana_potions/)

